The road to 800 drug-free day 17! Deadlifts were flying today on the Ohio Power Bar! I always like the super high deficit deadlifts because they really target the upper back harder than regular deadlifts. 

To further explain the concept of library deadlifts, they force you to engage the core, low back, and lats on the descent, which makes things much tougher and makes the transition back to regular deadlifts a whole lot easier. 

I’m not trying to go slow on the way down, rather jm setting the bar down as gently as possible. You’ll feel the difference! Give it a try sometime! Throwback to 2017 Reebok Record Breakers. This was my best ever competition deadlift and one of the many narrow misses with 400 kg (882 lbs). Grip was something I didn’t dial in well until the last few years, but the two things that have really helped me have been devoting 2 days per week in meet prep to double overhand static holds in a rack and static holds with the Captains of Crush Grippers. 

I like to do three total sets for max time on static holds and I like to do three max time singles per side on the Captains of Crush with the #2.5-3 Gripper. This hits two different types of grip and was what really helped solidify things later on, along with the transition to hook grip.

I had to pace myself and leave some in the tank considering I had three more sets of this, but deadlifts were flying today on the stiff-bar! 

➡️One of the biggest things I try to teach people is that it’s often best to hold back and not always train to failure or as heavy as possible. 

🚨You can’t be peaked year round. You have to gradually build up your strength and leave reps in the tank to maximize your peak. Patience is the name of the game. The tortoise will always beat the hare… @kelleyrubish 

Also shout-out to my baby girl shrieking in the background 😂

Is the culprit really insulin resistance and not elevated LDL…we know that statins significantly lower both LDL and triglycerides, but these studies point to elevated triglyceride levels actually being the bigger problem and not LDL, which is why statins may reduce all cause mortality to some extent. Dig deeper into even further studies and the use of statin use is suspect at best. Statins have no positive effect on Lipoprotein(a) levels either, which is likely a much bigger issue than elevated LDL levels. 

https://doi.org/10.1093/eurheartj/ehy902

***2.5 Years off Testosterone/Anabolic Steroids Update***220 lbs (100 kg) bodyweight. Use code “PETE” for 10% off @marekhealth bloodwork panels

1) I’ve had a dozen panels done since coming off everything and my total testosterone had never risen above 409 ng/dL. So this is a significant uptick. Estradiol had never risen above 14 pg/mL either. Many said I would have to hop on TRT but staying patient has appeared to pay off. There are major signs of recovery now.

2) My free testosterone levels are quite low, but this is where supplementing with something like 10 mgs of Boron could bring the SHBG down some and raise the free test levels.

3) My insulin sensitivity has never been better. I’m very proud of the insulin and HBa1c levels. I’ve been very diligent with my cardio regimen the past few months.

4) C-Reactive Protein is a great tool for measuring systemic inflammation and this also really couldn’t be better. Im very pleased with this.

5) ApoB is in a decent spot without statin or ezetimibe intervention. I’d still like to bring this down some. ApoB is a much more important proxy for heart health than traditional Lipid biomarkers like LDL and HDL

It was one of the toughest moments of my life yesterday. I had to lay one of my best friends to rest and send her on her way to heaven. Never in a million years did I think this day was coming so soon a week ago. Little did I know that she was in end stage kidney failure and her organs were shutting down until it was too late. My heart feels like it’s been ripped out.

Lucy was my dog for the last 6.5 years. @kelleyrubish picked her out for me at the animal shelter because she was the saddest looking dog in there. I’ve shed more tears in the last few days than I’ve shed in years. She was always there for me. We had many road trips up to Wisconsin together, we went on countless walks, she slept by my side when I lived by myself, she was everything I could have asked for in a dog. 

I miss the heck out of her. The pain has been very real these past couple days, as I knew I’d have to let her go. If anything, this moment has made me realize we all have a finite time together. Do not take your loved ones for granted. I thought we had many more years together, only for that time to end so abruptly. And that hurts more than you know…Appreciate what you have. Live in the moment. Spend time with your loved ones. Sports, social media, and the rest of it are merely distractions. Nobody will ever regret missing the big game, but you’ll regret not making the most of your time together when one of your loved ones inevitably passes away. Do not live passively.

I believe in the Lord. I believe in Jesus. And I believe in heaven. Do all dogs go to heaven? I’d like to think so. There are no more loyal, loving, forgiving animals on this earth. Someday I’ll see you on the other side Lucy. ❤️

➡️Creatinine is not the most accurate indicator of kidney health and you can see the difference in slides #1 and #2. 

➡️Cystatin-C is a much better indicator of overall kidney health as it isn’t influenced by muscle mass. Having more muscle mass will often skew the Creatinine and subsequent eGFR reading (estimated glomerular filtration rate) and make it look like your kidneys are functioning less effectively than they are. The higher your eGFR, the better. 

💪My recommendation is to get your Cystatin-C checked once per year to get a better picture of your kidney health if you have quite a bit of muscle mass. 

💊Astragalus is the best all around supplement you can take to support healthy kidneys. This was checked after 6 weeks of taking @leviathannutrition Kidney Support, which contains Astragalus. While not something I take all the time, I can vouch for kidney supports efficacy and you can use my code (Pete) on any leviathan supplements for 10% off. 

ADMA is a newer biomarker that is an inhibitor of Nitric Oxide production and a biomarker you want to aim to keep as low as possible. The higher the level, the greater the indicator of cardiovascular disease. Again, this isn’t something I’d check all the time, but once a year it’s not a bad idea to see what some of these inflammatory biomarkers are at. I use @marekhealth for all of my panels because they’re the only ones who will allow you to create a completely custom panel. Code (Pete)

I was at a point in life where I felt somewhat stagnant, beat up, and not on my A-game anymore as a powerlifter. 

When you hit that point, you can either stay where you are and get passed by, or pivot and reinvent yourself. The chapter of my life where I was 250 lbs bodyweight and totaling 2100 lbs raw may be over, but the book isn’t closed. There are new chapters unfolding.

And this new 200 lb version of me that’s into hybrid fitness may not appeal to everyone, but I have never felt better. 

The goals I have now get me feeling excited every time I wake up in the morning. To be chasing after a sub 1:40 half marathon and 550 squat is exciting stuff!

And today was a further confidence builder. To be 15 seconds off race pace on a hilly course in muggy conditions and have it feel that good was huge for me. And then to come back and squat sets of paused triples at 375 immediately after furthered that confidence. 

You just have to stack wins day by day. I hit some huge milestones last week. 700+ miles ran for the year. A 6:37 minute mile.

I feel great. I know I’m on track. And I have variables I can play with on squat. Adding in sleeves. Taking out the pause. Switching to low bar. Adding back in Creatine. 550 doesn’t seem insurmountable.

Take it one day at a time. Stack the wins with whatever you’re chasing. It will pay off. I have a great wife @kelleyrubish and running coach @serv_fitness in my corner. And the Lord watches over me. Philippians 4:13 There are still 4.5 months left in the year. I’m not waiting until New Years to get after it. Let’s roll!
